Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that flowers can provide a good example of intermediate dominance. When a white flower and red flower are crossed, they will produce all pink offspring, with the parent colors being masked. If two pink flowers are crossed, however, they can produce red, white, and pink offspring.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that multiple alleles of most genes are usually found in wild populations since these populations are not constricted to a small, lab-sized population with which they can reproduce. Therefore there is greater diversity.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that if genes interact in certain ways, the F2 generation of a dihybrid cross will display phenotypes that deviate from the expected 9:3:3:1 ratios. This is because one gene may mask the effect of another gene, or together they may produce an entirely different effect.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that two mutations affecting the same trait may not be in the same gene. To test for this, two mutants could be crossed. If their offspring is also mutant, the mutations affect the same gene. If the offspring is normal, the mutations affect different genes.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

phenomenonA Multiple alleles of most genes are usually found in wild populations.
phenomenonA[comment] The importance of multiple alleles of the same gene can be related to the survivability of prokaryotes due to genetic mutation. Bacteria, although much different genetically compared to eukaryotes, have the ability to mutate often and possibly pass these mutations to their progeny. Something as simple as a small change in the cell membrane can prevent a potentially harmful virus from destroying an entire population. Overall, multiple alleles can allow for increased survivability.
phenomenonB Deviation from the expected 9:3:3:1 phenotypic ratios in the F2 generation of a dihybrid cross indicated different kinds of gene interactions
phenomenonB[comment] If the phenotypic ratio does not follow the classic Mendelian 9:3:3:1 ratio then this is an indicator of a different mode of inheritance. For example, the probability to pass on a certain autosomal recessive trait (Aa) would be different than the probability to receive a specific blood type (A, B, AB, O).
groupTime391 1733.1

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that partial dominance results in the blended expression of multiple phenotypes. I understand that codominance results in both alleles being expressed fully.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that multiple alleles are necessary for genetic variation and thus survival. I understand that a null allele is a gene that lacks its normal function. An example of multiple alleles in populations would be the ABO blood type, with possible combinations of AO, BO, AB, and O (This is also and example of how one allele could be masked: AO= type A)
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that in epistasis multiple alleles on the same locus of a gene can be expressed simultaneously. I understand that lethal alleles will alter the Mendelian ratio.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that complementation occurs when two different homozygous recessive mutations can produce the same phenotype. I understand that complementation can only occur when the two alleles are on different genes.

knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Some gene pairs can influence the functioning of another gene pair. For example, a homozygous recessive genotype of either gene can cause both genes to be nonfunctional. In this case, the ratio compares functional gene pair combinations to nonfunctional; a 9:3:3:1 ratio may become 9:7 because nine combinations are heterozygous or homozygous dominant and seven have at least one set of homozygous recessive alleles.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Complementation occurs when two mutations are on two genes that make the function whole, restoring wild type. If the mutation occurs at different locations on the same gene, no complementation occurs and wild type is not restored.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Some genes interact in such a way that leaves one allele dominant and another allele recessive. The dominant allele, no matter whether the genotype is homozygous or heterozygous does not show any of the recessive allele. Other genes interact so that if the genotype is heterozygous there will be an intermediate phenotype that has characteristics of both alleles. This is haploinsufficiency.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] When a species has three or more alleles, there is a much more unique pattern of inheritance. This must be studied in a population though. Any two individuals will have at most two different alleles. In a population, there can be many forms of the same gene. Wild populations are most likely to have multiple alleles because any alleles that result in a deficiency will likely lead to unsuccessful reproduction for that animal meaning that its genes will not be passed on.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] If the 9:3:3:1 phenotypic ratio is not followed that means that the genes interact in a way that masks one or does not allow pure dominance over one allele. The different ratios are often a result of genes being in the same pathway, recessive epistasis, dominant epistasis, mutations, or other causes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Complementation testing is often used for recessive traits. They are also called cis—trans tests because cis is used to describe mutations that occur on the same chromosome and trans is used to describe mutations on different chromosomes. In the cis test, a functional protein is always produced and the trans test produces a heterozygote that has different mutations from the different parents and the functional protein is only produced if that mutations are on different genes.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Alleles are alternative forms of a gene (e.g. a flower color may be white, another flower may be purple). This means that the gene for color is expressed in two different forms, either white or purpl
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] An allele is a variant of a gene. A gene may have a number of alleles. All alleles of the same gene exist at the same locus. A cell holds 2 alleles of each gene. One allele from mom, one allele from dad. When a gene has only 2 alleles, then that's the simple case we're used to seeing. For example, the trait for height in peas is governed by T and t. TT and Tt gives tall plants, and tt gives short ones.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Generally, interacting genes in two different pathways produce an F2 with four phenotypes corresponding to the four possible genotypic classes, as in the snake example. However, when the mutations are in one biological pathway, different ratios are seen. Usually there are only two or three phenotypes resulting from various combinations of the genotypic classes. Likewise, the F2 ratio is a modification of the 9:3:3:1 ratio, produced by grouping various components of the ratio.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] he complementation test is relevant for recessive traits (traits normally not present in the phenotype due to masking by a dominant allele). In instances when two parent organisms each carry two mutant genes in a homozygous recessive state, causing the recessive trait to be expressed, the complementation test can determine whether the recessive trait will be expressed in the next generation.

Incomplete dominance is a result of haplo-insufficiency where neither allele is dominant or sufficient enough to produce the wild type phenotype. In other cases certain allelic combinations result in one being masked by the other. In epistasis one gene blocks the expression of another gene because they may lay on the same pathway or interact in some way.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] When three or more alleles of a gene exist inheritance may become unique. Multiple alleles can only be studied in populations because a diploid organism can only have two homologous genes at the same loci where an allele of that gene can exist. If we study the members of a species we can see that there are many alternative forms that can exist.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] In situations of lethal alleles, epistasis, or supressors will change the 3:1 ratio of Mendel's F2 monohybrid generation. Therefore if we conduct dihybrid crosses the typical dihybrid ratio 9:3:3:1 will be modified. For example if genes are in the same pathway one gene will affect the other resulting in a in a 9:7 ratio.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Complementation tests whether phenotypically identical mutants carry the mutation on the same gene or not. This is important because we must remember that several genes can lead to a certain phenotype and that a mutant can be a result from mutations on multiple genes working together. We can conduct this test on whether Drosophila flies have wings or not. Lets say all offspring have normal wings. This means the mutations were on different genes and complemented each other.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] This allelic combination of an intermediate phenotype is called codominance. In the heterozygote, both alleles can be seen. For example, ABO blood typing results in a blood cell having A and B antigens if they are AB. In other words, neither A or B is dominant over the other so they are both seen in the phenotype. If one allele is completely dominant over the other allele, then the recessive allele will be masked in the heterozygote, creating a 3:1 phenotypic ratio.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that multiple alleles occurs when there are 3 or more alleles for a gene of a diploid organism. An example is ABO blood typing. A diploid organism can only have 2 of these alleles even though there are more than only 2 allele options.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that two gene pairs interacting can create weird ratios that are variations of the 9:3:3:1 ratio of a dihybrid cross. These weird ratios can result when regulatory genes prevent the wild-type gene from being functional. Different processes can cause this action. Examples include suppression and lethality where both mutants are needed to make this gene functional.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that complementation testing can determine if two mutations that are affecting the same trait are actually in the same gene. These mutations are isolated independently and are bred to see if the mutant is a recessive type.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

phenomenonA Deviation from the expected 9:3:3:1 phenotypic ratios in the F2 generation of a dihybrid cross indicated different kinds of gene interactions
phenomenonA[comment] As most students initially learn, Mendel observed that there is a dihybrid ration of 9:3:3:1. However, what he was unable to see was that a concept known as epistasis has the ability to produce modified results by altering the way in which genes interact with each other. For example, recessive epistasis is when a recessive allele suppresses the expression of the dominant allele. Dominant epistasis occurs when a dominant allele masks the expression of another allele (not necessarily a recessive allele). Complementary gene interaction is the concept that in order for a certain phenotype to be produced, there must be at least one dominant allele on each gene. As genes are the building blocks of who we are, the interactions of genes are incredibly important in the ways in which we appear, our mannerisms, and how we function. Although alleles are transferred from one generation to the next, their expression will ultimately be determined by the alleles around them, and subsequently is not as "black and white" as Mendel once thought.
phenomenonB Multiple alleles of most genes are usually found in wild populations.
phenomenonB[comment] The concept that some allelic occur in multiples within a population is called multiple alleles. The most obvious example of this biological phenomenon is the human blood type. As most people know, there are four different types of blood one can have. These are A, B, AB, or O. Individuals with blood type A have the A antigen on their red blood cells and antibodies against the B antigen. Similarly, individuals who have B blood have the B antigen and antibodies against the A antigen. Individuals with AB have both A and B antigens on their red blood cells and individuals with O blood type do not have either antigen on their red blood cells and their blood serum contains antibodies against A and B antigens. As blood types are transferred from generation to generation, only certain combinations will produce a certain blood type. For example, in order for an individual to be born with AB blood type, they must have both the A and B alleles. If someone has blood type A, then they may only have one copy of the A allele. The same is true for B. Relating back to the original question, there are multiple alleles that a person can have to produce a particular blood type.

knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand this concept very well because it is the basis of our blood type as humans. I understand that there are many different alleles that can code for a single gene to produce a very diverse population. Certain alleles and combinations of alleles will produce a certain blood type, while the lack of others will produce a completely different blood type. Furthermore, the basis for the different alleles in populations is through mutations, by which we are very diverse.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The textbook 9:3:3:1 phenotypic ratio is not the rule in genotyping of a dihybrid cross. The reasoning for this is that there are many different genes that can influence and modify other genes. Some genes have the ability to completely mask a certain genotypic expression, while others are complementary in other gene's expression. Phenotypic ratios are ultimately the result of the interactions of alleles in the gene.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand the use of complementation analysis. I understand that this testing is used to identify if only a single gene or multiple genes are causing a certain mutation in a phenotype. Ultimately, this could be due to the fact that many different alleles influence a certain phenotypic trait. So, a mutation in any one of the alleles could be causing the mutation.

knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that the complementation test is useful for determining if a recessive trait will be present in the offspring. phenomenonA Some allelic combinations result in an intermediate phenotype while others result in one allele being masked.
phenomenonA[comment] I think that gene interactions that result in either an intermediate phenotype or one allele being masked is interesting because it adds another level to the typical dominant/recessive distinction. When we talk about genetics in the cut and dry dominant/recessive way, it is a lot less interesting that when we talk about how genes interact and the different effects of allelic combinations.
phenomenonB Multiple alleles of most genes are usually found in wild populations.
phenomenonB[comment] Having multiple alleles in wild populations creates even more genetic diversity and possible outcomes. Having multiple alleles help protect against the possibility of inheriting two alleles with mutations on the same gene. I think examples of maladaptive traits found in inbred family lines is especially interesting.
groupTime391 393.38

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] When allelic combinations result in an intermediate phenotype, this is because both alleles are expressed and produce gene products that affect the phenotype. As with many types of flowers, heterozygotes for color can result in a new, intermediate color. In other cases, the presence of just one wild type allele can compensate for the lose of gene products of a mutant nonfunctional allele.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] As seen in the example of ABO blood types, having multiple alleles of the gene that results in various carbohydrates in the membrane of cells creates a range of possible phenotypes. Having multiple alleles for the same gene in a population helps protect against deleterious mutations.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] By looking at phenotypic ratios, we can study and predict what interactions genes have with each other. When deviations from expected ratios occur, it indicates a variety of possible interactions. One such interaction could be the ability of one allele to mask the gene products (or lack there of) from the other allele.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Complementation testing involves the incorporation of one allele from one strain of mutants with one allele from a different strain of mutants, with both strains having the same phenoytypic mutation. If the resulting offspring of this cross still retain the mutant phenotype, this indicates that the two mutations lie on the same gene. If the offspring are wild type, this indicates that the mutations lie on different genes, and that lost gene products are compensated for.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] An intermediate phenotype is a biological trait that is heritable and shows greater prevalence in unaffected relatives of patients than in the general population.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Such a "wild type" allele was regarded as dominant, common, and normal, in contrast to "mutant" alleles regarded as recessive, rare, and frequently deleterious.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] 9:7 is observed when  a homozygous recessive mutation in either or both of two different genes results in the same mutant phenotype (complementation
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] The appropriate genetic question to ask is whether any of the mutations are in a single gene, or whether each mutations represents one of the several genes necessary for a phenotype to be expressed. The simplest test to distinguish between the two possibilities is the complementation test.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] The intermediate phenotypes result from one allele not being strong enough to show produce enough of a protein or something else to cover the effects of the other allele. Other times, on allele is clearly shown to be dominant and it is the only one that shows.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Many alleles of a single gene makes sense as we see such a variation in nature within one species. We can see many variations on a single characteristic such as eye color or skin tone.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The deviation from the normal ratio makes more sense of "problems" we often see with reproduction and these observed deviations can explain many medical phenomena. These deviations can be mapped and used in genetic therapy or used as a way for parents to see their risk for being a carrier for a specific allele.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Complementation takes place if two alleles on two seperate genes have mutated to affect the same gene, and this produces the wild-type phenotype.
